Object.Field: Configuration #1 - IKM Oracle Partition Exchange Load - Asynchronous - No Flow Control - Without Validation

This package uses the scenarios of the mapping called "Configuration #1 - IKM Oracle Partition Exchange Load - No Flow Control - Disable Constraints - Without Validation" to perform a full load of the partitioned table.
The scenarios in this package perform the full load of the partitioned table with the IKM Oracle Partition Exchange Load.
This package performs the partition exchange operation without validation; thus, it is expected that source data belongs to the partition.
The scenarios in this package do not use flow control (CKM Oracle). It assumes that source data is clean (no table constraints issues will be found when enabling table constraints).
The first scenario changes the statistics preference of the partitioned table to incremental. Also, it disables table constraints on the partitioned table, and it loads the first partition.
The next scenario loads the next set of partitions in parallel (asynchronous mode).
Local indexes are rebuilt after every partition exchange (in all 3 scenarios: first, next, and last).
The last scenario loads the last partition, rebuilds global indexes, enables table constraints, and gather incremental statistics for the partitioned table.
The package waits 5 seconds before launching the next partition load. This is to ensure that the PARTITION_MONTH variable gets refreshed accordingly before assigning its value to the next scenario.
The "Wait For Partition Uploads" ensures that all previous partitions are loaded successfully before executing the last partition load.
This strategy offers the best performance. Here are some of the benefits:
Advantages:
1. This strategy offers the fastest way of uploading data into the partitioned table, since the exchange operation is done without validation. 2. Partitions are loaded asynchronously, in parallel. 3. Table constraints are disabled during the entire upload operation. 4. Local indexes are rebuilt after every partition exchange load. 5. Global indexes are rebuilt only once, after the last partition exchange operation. This may be faster than updating global indexes on every exchange operation. 6. Incremental statistics are gathered after the last partition exchange load operation.
Disadvantages:
1. Source data must be clean since flow control is not used with this strategy. 2. It may take time to rebuild global indexes.
